description: From Middle English uplondish, oplondysch, uplondysch, from Old English uplendisc (“uplandish”); equivalent to upland +‎ -ish.

adjectives.description: uplandish (comparative more uplandish, superlative most uplandish)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Of or pertaining to uplands; pertaining to or situated in country districts.
(obsolete) Rustic, rude, boorish; countrified, unsophisticated, or uncivilized.
Wild or savage; mountainous, or dwelling in the mountains.
